'''Ralph Jasper Faudree''' (August 23, 1939 – January 13, 2015) was a [[mathematician]], a professor of mathematics and the former [[Provost (education)|provost]] of the [[University of Memphis]].<ref name="mtp">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120808235856/http://www.memphis.edu/mediaroom/releases/aug12/faudree.htm],  Faudree to Step Down as University Provost - retrieved 2014-04-22.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Former U of M Provost Ralph Faudree Dies|date=14 January 2015|website=News Blog, Memphis News and Events, Memphis Flyer|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/NewsBlog/archives/2015/01/14/former-u-of-m-provost-dies-from-self-inflicted-gunshot-wound}}</ref>

Faudree was born in [[Durant, Oklahoma]].<ref name="tca"/> He did his undergraduate studies at [[Oklahoma Baptist University]], graduating in 1961,<ref name="cv">[http://www.memphis.edu/provost/pdfs/faudree_cv.pdf Curriculum vitae] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728011319/http://www.memphis.edu/provost/pdfs/faudree_cv.pdf |date=July 28, 2011 }} from Memphis U.</ref> and received his Ph.D. in 1964 from [[Purdue University]] under the supervision of Eugene Schenkman<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=14716}}</ref> (1922–1977).<ref>[http://civilianpublicservice.org/workers/8931 Schenkman, Eugene V., The Civilian Public Service Story]</ref><ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/dailyrecord/obituary.aspx?n=agnes-schenkman&pid=146521048 Agnes Schenkman's obituary, 2010, The Daily Record]</ref><ref>[http://www.mocavo.com/Eugene-Schenkman-1922-1977-Social-Security-Death-Index/03583540447324513287 EUGENE SCHENKMAN (1922–1977)]</ref> Faudree was an instructor at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and an assistant professor at the [[University of Illinois]] before joining the Memphis State University faculty as an associate professor in 1971.<ref name="cv"/> Memphis State became renamed as the University of Memphis in 1994, and Faudree was appointed as provost in 2001.<ref name="mtp"/><ref name="tca"/><ref name="cv"/>

Faudree specialized in [[combinatorics]], and specifically in [[graph theory]] and [[Ramsey theory]]. He published more than 200 mathematical papers on these topics together with such notable mathematicians as [[Béla Bollobás]], [[Stefan Burr]], [[Paul Erdős]], [[Ron Gould (mathematician)|Ron Gould]], [[András Gyárfás]], [[Brendan McKay]], [[C. C. Rousseau|Cecil Rousseau]], [[Richard Schelp]], [[Miklós Simonovits]], [[Joel Spencer]], and [[Vera Sós]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/mathscinet/search/author.html?mrauthid=65425&Submit=Search List of publications]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} in [[MathSciNet]], retrieved 2010-05-24.</ref> He was the 2005 recipient of the [[Euler Medal]] for his contributions to combinatorics.<ref name="tca">{{citation|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/apr/30/u-of-m-provost-in-prestigious-company/|title=U of M provost receives Euler Medal for math|first=Ginger|last=Porter|journal=[[The Commercial Appeal]]|date=April 30, 2008}}.</ref>  His [[Erdős number]] was 1: he cowrote 50 joint papers with Paul Erdős beginning in 1976 and was among the three mathematicians who most frequently co-authored with Erdős.<ref>[http://www.oakland.edu/enp/ The Erdős number project].</ref>

